# Experiment No. 2

# Title

Execute DDL commands to manage Database using SQL.

---

# Aim

To study and execute DDL (Data Definition Language) commands for managing database structure using SQL.

---

# Theory

DDL (Data Definition Language) commands are used to define, create, modify, and delete database objects such as tables, views, and indexes.

These commands affect the structure of the database.
DDL commands automatically save changes permanently in the database because they perform **AUTO COMMIT**.

DDL commands are mainly used by database administrators and developers while designing database systems.

---

# Types of DDL Commands

| Command  | Purpose                                |
| -------- | -------------------------------------- |
| CREATE   | Creates a new table or database object |
| ALTER    | Modifies existing table structure      |
| DROP     | Deletes table permanently              |
| TRUNCATE | Removes all records from table         |
| RENAME   | Changes table name                     |

---

# 1. CREATE Command

## Theory

The CREATE command is used to create a new table in the database.

---

## Syntax

```sql id="6o9ht8"
CREATE TABLE table_name(
 column1 datatype(size),
 column2 datatype(size),
 column3 datatype(size)
);
```

---

## Example

```sql id="79l9q0"
CREATE TABLE Student(
 RollNo NUMBER(5),
 Name VARCHAR2(20),
 City VARCHAR2(20)
);
```

---

## Explanation

* `RollNo` stores student roll number
* `Name` stores student name
* `City` stores city name

After execution, a table named `Student` is created successfully.

---

# 2. ALTER Command

## Theory

The ALTER command is used to modify the structure of an existing table.

It can:

* Add columns
* Modify columns
* Delete columns

---

## Syntax for Adding Column

```sql id="6sf9fm"
ALTER TABLE table_name
ADD column_name datatype(size);
```

---

## Example

```sql id="t9z6kq"
ALTER TABLE Student
ADD Marks NUMBER(3);
```

---

## Explanation

A new column `Marks` is added to the Student table.

---

# 3. DROP Command

## Theory

The DROP command permanently deletes the table and all its data.

---

## Syntax

```sql id="c5cq4j"
DROP TABLE table_name;
```

---

## Example

```sql id="9u4d1p"
DROP TABLE Student;
```

---

## Explanation

The Student table is removed completely from the database.

---

# 4. TRUNCATE Command

## Theory

The TRUNCATE command removes all records from a table but keeps the table structure.

It is faster than DELETE command.

---

## Syntax

```sql id="0fj8a3"
TRUNCATE TABLE table_name;
```

---

## Example

```sql id="8bjlwm"
TRUNCATE TABLE Student;
```

---

## Explanation

All records from Student table are deleted, but table structure remains unchanged.

---

# 5. RENAME Command

## Theory

The RENAME command changes the name of an existing table.

---

## Syntax

```sql id="dlk4n5"
RENAME old_table_name TO new_table_name;
```

---

## Example

```sql id="0eivdg"
RENAME Student TO Student_Info;
```

---

## Explanation

The table name changes from `Student` to `Student_Info`.

---

# Complete Program

```sql id="7l4mjlwm"
CREATE TABLE Student(
 RollNo NUMBER(5),
 Name VARCHAR2(20),
 City VARCHAR2(20)
);

ALTER TABLE Student
ADD Marks NUMBER(3);

RENAME Student TO Student_Info;

TRUNCATE TABLE Student_Info;

DROP TABLE Student_Info;
```

---

# Output

* Table created successfully
* Column added successfully
* Table renamed successfully
* Records deleted successfully
* Table dropped successfully

---

# Advantages of DDL Commands

* Helps manage database structure
* Easy modification of tables
* Improves database organization
* Supports database maintenance

---

# Conclusion

Thus, DDL commands such as CREATE, ALTER, DROP, TRUNCATE, and RENAME were successfully executed to manage the database structure using SQL.
